sub_subject.name: Human Geography (Geopolitics, Culture & Economics)
sub_subject.description: 13-year academic progression (K-12) for Human Geography (Geopolitics, Culture & Economics) (Geography)

objectives.objective_text: Identify buildings that look like churches or temples.
Name a farm field vs. a city street.
Identify 'placemaking' (making a place feel like home).
Identify that people in different places speak different languages.
Name a holiday celebrated in another country.
Identify English as one of many languages.
Name a country where they don't speak English.
Identify loanwords we use (like 'pizza' or 'safari').
Identify toys made in China.
Name food from other countries (bananas, chocolate).
Identify famous global brands (McDonalds, Nike).
Identify that some places are rich and some are poor.
Name clean water and school as things everyone needs.
Identify Literacy Rate (reading).
Identify a canal as a water road.
Name the Panama Canal.
Identify a 'Chokepoint' (bottleneck).
Identify walls and castles.
Name mountains as hard to cross.
Identify natural barriers.
Identify farms that grow food.
Name corn, wheat, and rice.
Identify gas stations for cars.
Name the sun and wind as power.
Identify solar panels and wind turbines.
Identify gold and silver as valuable.
Name rocks that we use to make things.
Identify which countries have the most gold.
Identify fresh water vs. salt water.
Name a well or a dam.
Identify the Nile River as life for Egypt.
Identify a family with many children.
Name a family with few children.
Identify Birth Rate and Death Rate.
Identify moving to a new house.
Name a person who moved from another country.
Identify the difference between an Immigrant and an Emigrant.
Identify where lots of people live (cities).
Name places where few people live (deserts, ice).
Identify the 'empty' quarters of the world.
Identify where houses are.
Name where stores and factories are.
Identify residential zones.
Identify a farm vs. a city.
Name a skyscraper.
Identify a 'Megacity' (very big city).
Recall that people change the land.
Observe statues or monuments in a town.
Recall that God made people different and beautiful.
Observe that houses look different in different places.
Recall that people move and take words with them.
Listen to the sound of a foreign language.
Recall that we can talk to people far away.
Observe that the world is connected.
Recall that we should help those in need.
Observe pictures of life in different countries.
Recall that ships carry toys and clothes.
Observe a narrow place in the sea.
Recall that an island is safe from walking armies.
Observe the ocean protecting a country.
Recall that some food grows in hot places (bananas) and some in cold.
Observe where our breakfast comes from.
Recall that we need electricity for lights.
Observe coal or oil in pictures.
Recall that batteries need special metals.
Observe that mining digs holes in the ground.
Recall that we need water to live.
Observe that some places are very dry.
Recall that people live longer now.
Observe that babies need care.
Recall that people move for jobs or safety.
Observe that moving is hard work.
Recall that people like to live near water.
Observe a map with dots for people.
Recall that parks are for playing.
Observe that downtown has tall buildings.
Recall that more people are moving to cities.
Observe traffic and lights in the city.
Summarize how people change the land to fit their culture (terraced farming).
Explain why cities in Europe look different than US cities.
Explain the concept of 'Sequent Occupance' (layers of history).
Summarize what 'Culture' means (food, clothes, language, beliefs).
Explain that language groups people together.
Map the major religions of the world.
Explain the difference between folk culture and pop culture.
Defend the value of cultural diversity using the Babel reversal (Pentecost/Revelation 7).
Summarize how English spread around the world (Empire).
Explain why people in Brazil speak Portuguese.
Explain how isolation creates new dialects.
Defend the preservation of minority languages.
Summarize how goods move around the world (container ships).
Explain that companies work in many countries (TNCs).
Explain outsourcing.
Defend the benefits of free trade while acknowledging its flaws.
Summarize what 'Standard of Living' means.
Explain High Income (HIC) vs. Low Income (LIC) countries.
Explain the Brandt Line (North/South divide).
Defend a holistic view of human flourishing.
Summarize why the Suez Canal is important.
Explain what a 'shortcut' does for ships.
Explain the Turkish Straits (Bosporus/Dardanelles).
Defend the necessity of freedom of navigation operations.
Summarize why Switzerland is hard to invade (Mountains).
Explain why Britain being an island helped it.
Explain the concept of 'Strategic Depth'.
Defend the theory that geography influences political destiny.
Summarize the 'Breadbasket' of the world (grain belts).
Explain what a cash crop is (coffee, cotton).
Locate the Rice Bowl of Asia.
Explain the concept of 'Food Security'.
Defend the moral imperative to feed the hungry.
Summarize where oil comes from (Middle East, USA, Russia).
Explain the difference between renewable (sun) and non-renewable (oil).
Explain the 'Resource Curse' (Paradox of Plenty).
Summarize why we need lithium and cobalt (phones/batteries).
Explain that minerals are hidden underground.
Explain the environmental impact of open-pit mining.
Defend fair trade practices in mineral extraction.
Summarize why rivers are important for cities.
Explain what a drought is.
Explain the process of Desalination.
Defend access to clean water as a human right.
Summarize why families used to be bigger (farm work).
Explain why people live longer (medicine).
Explain why some countries are shrinking (Stage 5).
Defend the biblical view of children as a blessing.
Summarize 'Push Factors' (bad things) and 'Pull Factors' (good things).
Explain what a Refugee is.
Explain 'Brain Drain' (smart people leaving).
Defend the biblical command to care for the sojourner.
Summarize why China and India have the most people.
Explain 'Population Density' (crowdedness).
Explain why the Northern Hemisphere has more people.
Defend the capacity of the earth to support humanity (anti-Malthusian).
Summarize the CBD (Central Business District).
Explain why factories are often near trains or rivers.
Explain the Rural-Urban Fringe.
Defend the need for zoning laws.
Summarize why people leave farms for the city (jobs).
Explain the difference between Rural and Urban.
Explain the concept of 'Urban Sprawl'.
Defend the role of cities as centers of culture and mission.
Compare a mosque, a synagogue, and a cathedral.
Analyze the impact of religion on the built environment.
Connect agricultural patterns to cultural diet.
Defend the theological significance of human stewardship of space.
Compare the culture of the Arab world with Latin America.
Analyze the concept of 'Cultural Diffusion' (how ideas spread).
Interpret a map of language families (Indo-European, Sino-Tibetan).
Connect ethnic groups to national borders (and conflicts).
Compare a 'Lingua Franca' (trade language) with a local dialect.
Analyze the spread of Arabic through religion.
Interpret the boundaries of the Romance Languages.
Connect colonization to current language maps.
Compare local food with global food.
Analyze the benefits (cheap goods) and costs (pollution, low wages) of globalization.
Interpret the 'shrinking world' effect (time-space compression).
Connect the internet to cultural exchange.
Compare life expectancy in different places.
Analyze the HDI (Human Development Index).
Interpret GDP per capita.
Connect health care and education to wealth.
Compare going around Africa vs. using the canal.
Analyze the Strait of Malacca and global trade.
Interpret the vulnerability of the Strait of Hormuz (Oil).
Connect global prices to blockages in these waterways.
Compare a flat country (Poland) with a mountainous one (Afghanistan).
Analyze the 'North European Plain' as an invasion route.
Interpret the strategic value of the Khyber Pass.
Connect geography to the outcome of historic battles.
Compare subsistence farming (eating what you grow) with commercial farming.
Analyze the Von Thunen Model of land use.
Interpret the impact of the Green Revolution.
Connect climate zones to specific crop production.
Compare a country with lots of oil to one with none.
Analyze the strategic importance of the Strait of Hormuz.
Interpret the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
Connect energy wealth to economic development.
Defend the ethical stewardship of extraction.
Compare a diamond mine with a coal mine.
Analyze the supply chain of a smartphone.
Interpret the conflict in regions with high mineral wealth (e.g., DRC).
Connect China's dominance in Rare Earth Elements to technology.
Compare a place with plenty of water vs. a place with little.
Interpret the depletion of aquifers (underground water).
Connect water scarcity to potential conflict.
Compare a young country with an old country.
Analyze the 4 (or 5) stages of the DTM.
Interpret the reasons for the population explosion in Stage 2.
Connect education of women to lower birth rates.
Compare voluntary moving with forced moving.
Analyze the Great Migration in the US.
Interpret the flow of remittances (money sent home).
Connect war and famine to migration crises.
Compare a dense city with a sparse farm area.
Analyze the physical factors affecting settlement (climate, soil).
Interpret a dot-density map.
Connect coastal living to economic opportunity.
Compare the inner city with the outer edge.
Analyze the Burgess Concentric Zone Model.
Interpret the Hoyt Sector Model.
Connect land value to building height.
Compare a Suburb with the City Center.
Analyze the problems of rapid urbanization (slums, traffic).
Interpret the growth of cities in Asia and Africa.
Connect industrialization to the growth of cities.
Evaluate the tension between modernization and heritage preservation.
Evaluate the impact of Westernization on indigenous cultures.
Evaluate the political power dynamics of official languages.
Evaluate the impact of globalization on local cultures (homogenization).
Evaluate the Gini Coefficient (inequality).
Evaluate the impact of a melting Arctic Ocean (new trade routes).
Evaluate the defensive advantage of the 'First Island Chain' in Asia.
Evaluate the sustainability of monoculture vs. polyculture.
Evaluate the geopolitical shift toward green energy metals.
Evaluate the ethics of cobalt mining in conflict zones.
Evaluate the concept of 'Virtual Water' in trade.
Evaluate the economic consequences of an aging population.
Evaluate the ethics of border control vs. humanitarian aid.
Evaluate the environmental strain of high density.
Evaluate the accuracy of classic models in modern cities.
Evaluate the quality of life in megacities.
Analyze the conflict over the Grand Ethiopian Renaissance Dam.
Interpret the cultural imprint of colonialism on architecture.
Construct an analysis of a specific urban cultural landscape.
Synthesize the visible imprint of political ideology on the landscape.
Construct a profile of a cultural shatterbelt.
Synthesize the relationship between language extinction and cultural loss.
Construct a map of the Indo-European migration.
Synthesize the role of the internet in accelerating English dominance.
Construct a map of a global supply chain (e.g., iPhone).
Synthesize the reaction against globalization (nationalism/protectionism).
Construct a critique of using only money to measure success.
Synthesize the multiple factors that lead to development.
Construct a risk analysis of global chokepoints.
Synthesize the relationship between naval power and economic dominance.
Construct a geopolitical analysis of Russia's western border.
Synthesize military strategy with physical geography.
Construct an analysis of global food trade dependencies.
Synthesize the impact of climate change on agricultural belts.
Construct a map of global energy transit chokepoints.
Synthesize the relationship between energy security and foreign policy.
Construct a report on the geopolitics of the 'Green Energy Transition'.
Synthesize the strategic stockpiling of critical minerals.
Construct a case study on the politics of the Mekong or Jordan River.
Synthesize the future of 'Water Wars'.
Construct a population pyramid analysis for Japan vs. Nigeria.
Synthesize the DTM with economic development levels.
Construct a map of current global migration flows.
Synthesize the economic impact of migration on host countries.
Construct a demographic profile of a specific continent.
Synthesize technology's role in making uninhabitable areas habitable.
Construct a land-use map of the local city.
Synthesize the impact of gentrification on land use.
Construct a model of sustainable urban planning.
Synthesize the future of the 'Smart City'.
